content.description: Climb the center of the mediocre headwall on the northeast side of Strawberry Rock. A recent cleaning allowed the route to go on gear and is actually pretty neat. The moves are kind of wacky, and a bit complicated to protect well, but that all adds to the fun. It would be a popular top rope if it was cleaned up a bit. Pull over a bulge with a #2 at your feet and a difficult medium cam at your chest, pull up on a jug and place a micro-nut before pulling into the short crack. Traverse left where you can get a few black aliens, then back right to the the perfect hand crack finish.
content.protection: Micro nuts, micro cams, and .5-2". Anchor takes 2-3" cams.
content.location: Just to your left before going over towards the short 3rd class hiker's trail.

content.description: Part scramble, part climbing.  2 small cruxes might be 5.7 to 5.8 for a few feet to pass these parts, overall route is prob a 5.6.  Still very dirty and lichen on rock, needs cleaned and frequent use.Climb up to the left towards 1/2 way up.  Climb up a few feet, then climb towards center.  Finish going straight up again.
content.protection: Use cams, nuts, webbing, and chord to set up top anchor
content.location: East side of Strawberry Rock, on uphill part of trail, in relation to rest, the other parts of Strawberry Rock go down the hillside.

content.description: Solo up the lower wall, then continue up to the tree, passing a small cam placement on the way. Once on the ledge with the tree, the holds in the dihedral die off. Sling the base of the tree, then climb the tree for 15' until you can reach over from the tree and place a #4 cam before stepping back onto the wall where you then hit the crux pulling onto a sloping ledge. Finish up with a fun bulge that can be climbed as an offwidth, or with more exposed jugs on the outside.
content.protection: Nuts, a few small cams, and 4-5". Anchor with #2
content.location: Look for the obvious tree on the east face.

content.description: Solo up the lower wall (5.6) then cross the ledge towards the tree up above you. Make a move or two off the ledge then climb straight up the arete (right of the tree). There is some decent gear and the climbing is fun. 2/3 the way up there's a small ledge with a thin crack. Place a nest of micro cams and small nuts then set off on the crux, well above your gear. Pull the bulge with slopers and edges. You'll hit the first jug about 12' above your last piece. It's WILD and very fun. Anchor with slung block or a few #2s
content.protection: micro nuts and micro cams. Cams .3-1". Anchor with #2
content.location: Left side of the eastern face, just right of the tree midway up the wall.
